Turns out you're stuck with me.

00:00:13.715 --> 00:00:15.215
Nick Wagner. Your new captain.

00:00:15.349 --> 00:00:17.417
<i>Why are you being so
cool, right now? I hate this.</i>

00:00:17.552 --> 00:00:19.019
<i>I'm pissed. It should have been me.</i>

00:00:19.152 --> 00:00:22.155
Root beer on an unprotected
lip? You're a madman.

00:00:22.289 --> 00:00:23.658
The stress is getting to her.

00:00:23.791 --> 00:00:26.794
She goes rogue and something
happens She's not a cop.

00:00:26.928 --> 00:00:29.831
- <i>You okay?
- I told you it was - a clean shot. IA will clear me.</i>

00:00:29.964 --> 00:00:32.164
I'm not worried about your
badge. I'm worried about you.

00:00:32.199 --> 00:00:35.737
I just heard some rumors you
don't respond positively to authority.

00:00:35.870 --> 00:00:38.616
Sometimes I forget what it's like to
have somebody looking out for me.

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:40.073
See you tomorrow, Gillory.

00:00:40.207 --> 00:00:41.776
<i>- Any news?
- We found Roman.</i>

00:00:41.910 --> 00:00:43.745
<i>- Sending a photo.
- That's not Roman.</i>

00:00:43.878 --> 00:00:47.347
Roman asked me to put eyes on you and
Ava, just to make sure you two were okay.

00:00:47.481 --> 00:00:49.918
<i>Actually let myself believe
that he didn't abandon us.</i>

00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:51.418
I still believe that.

00:00:51.553 --> 00:00:52.696
<i>Arthur, I want that backpack.</i>

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:54.360
So, you think that whatever's in that bag

00:00:54.388 --> 00:00:57.090
will give you answers
and not just more questions?

00:01:23.651 --> 00:01:26.253
Huh. That's weird. You see that?

00:01:26.386 --> 00:01:27.421
Hmm.

00:01:27.889 --> 00:01:29.356
It's not coming back.

00:01:29.489 --> 00:01:30.558
I'ma go check it out.

00:01:37.031 --> 00:01:38.066
All clear so far.

00:01:52.212 --> 00:01:54.816
We good? What's your 20?

00:02:14.201 --> 00:02:16.169
Base, we got a guard down.

00:02:49.469 --> 00:02:53.107
- Good morning.
- Morgan, hey, hey. Are you and Ava okay?

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:54.709
Yeah, we're good. What's up?

00:02:54.842 --> 00:02:57.477
I'ma ask you straight up. You
have somebody following me again?

00:02:57.612 --> 00:02:59.179
What? No. What are you talking about?

00:02:59.312 --> 00:03:01.825
I don't know. I think someone's
been on my tail the past few days.

00:03:01.849 --> 00:03:03.584
Maybe it's nothing.

00:03:03.718 --> 00:03:06.718
Arthur, if you feel like you might be
in danger, you should call the police.

00:03:06.821 --> 00:03:08.523
<i>No, I don't think that's a good idea.</i>

00:03:08.656 --> 00:03:10.625
<i>Roman wasn't too keen
on the cops, remember?</i>

00:03:10.758 --> 00:03:12.069
What does this have to do with Roman?

00:03:12.093 --> 00:03:13.773
That's what I'm trying to figure out here.

00:03:13.861 --> 00:03:15.663
I mean.

00:03:15.797 --> 00:03:18.757
Were you able to learn anything about
what was inside that backpack of his?

00:03:22.003 --> 00:03:23.104
No, not yet.

00:03:23.905 --> 00:03:27.340
All right, well, look, maybe you
should just hide the bag for now,

00:03:27.474 --> 00:03:31.378
'cause whoever Roman's running from might
not want what's inside that bag getting out.

00:03:31.512 --> 00:03:32.680
You hear me?

00:03:34.549 --> 00:03:36.117
Yeah. Hey, I gotta go, okay?

00:03:36.249 --> 00:03:40.353
All right, well, look, just be
careful, all right, you and Ava.

00:03:40.487 --> 00:03:41.656
<i>Keep your head on a swivel.</i>

00:03:42.255 --> 00:03:43.658
You too.

00:03:49.197 --> 00:03:51.474
Ava and I didn't glove up at
home. Is that gonna be a problem?

00:03:51.498 --> 00:03:54.602
Only if you think you two might be
suspects in Roman's disappearance.

00:03:54.736 --> 00:03:55.879
I think you can count us out.

00:03:55.903 --> 00:03:57.505
And nothing in the bag look familiar?

00:03:57.638 --> 00:03:59.207
- Rang any bells?
- No.

00:03:59.339 --> 00:04:01.219
Also, Roman's not a huge fan
of law enforcement,

00:04:01.341 --> 00:04:02.886
so if we could just keep this between us.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.746
We'll keep the circle small.

00:04:04.879 --> 00:04:05.947
Thank you.

00:04:09.751 --> 00:04:11.351
What's going on?

00:04:11.485 --> 00:04:13.654
Just revisiting an old case.

00:04:16.224 --> 00:04:18.960
Call came in pretty high
profile. I want these two on it.

00:04:19.894 --> 00:04:20.928
Go, I got this.

00:04:22.697 --> 00:04:23.798
And close the door.

00:04:32.907 --> 00:04:34.474
She only arrived here last week.

00:04:34.609 --> 00:04:35.810
She have a name?

00:04:35.943 --> 00:04:37.612
<i>Young Girl Leaning On A Windowsill.</i>

00:04:37.745 --> 00:04:39.923
You guys are saying she a lot. We
are talking about a painting, right?

00:04:39.947 --> 00:04:42.083
Painted by Rembrandt in 1645.

00:04:42.216 --> 00:04:45.019
Up until last night, she was
here with our other Dutch masters.

00:04:45.153 --> 00:04:50.024
"This intimate portrait captures the most
fleeting moments of human expression."

00:04:50.158 --> 00:04:51.592
Sorry, I missed it.

00:04:51.726 --> 00:04:53.804
We'll need a list of museum
employees, anyone with access.

00:04:53.828 --> 00:04:57.165
Of course. Then I should call the
Fosters, so they hear it from me.

00:04:57.297 --> 00:04:58.599
The Fosters?

00:04:58.733 --> 00:05:00.477
Linda and Greg Foster
loaned us the Rembrandt.

00:05:00.501 --> 00:05:02.003
Any idea how much it's worth?

00:05:02.136 --> 00:05:06.439
I believe they paid over 20
million at auction a few years ago.

00:05:07.374 --> 00:05:08.854
- I'll get you that list.
- Thank you.

00:05:09.977 --> 00:05:12.547
Uh, we are Major Crimes, right?

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:14.782
I'm not really seeing
what's major about this.

00:05:14.916 --> 00:05:17.161
A theft of major artwork carries
a penalty of up to 10 years

00:05:17.185 --> 00:05:20.387
before the DA tacks on possession,
conspiracy, breaking and entering.

00:05:20.521 --> 00:05:22.023
Why? You prefer a dead body?

00:05:22.156 --> 00:05:24.692
No, I've just seen actual
missing girls get less attention.

00:05:24.826 --> 00:05:27.336
Well, like it or not, every news
outlet's gonna run with this story tonight.

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:29.640
Captain's probably trying to keep
this from blowing up in our faces.

00:05:29.664 --> 00:05:32.867
One guard said there was too much
smoke for her to get a look at the thief.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.903
Second guard took a blow to the
head, but I hear should be okay.

00:05:36.037 --> 00:05:37.305
So this is our point of entry?

00:05:37.437 --> 00:05:39.372
Yeah, and exit as far as we can tell.

00:05:39.507 --> 00:05:42.210
We had whatever this is sent
over to the lab for testing.

00:05:42.777 --> 00:05:44.822
Well, put a rush on the results
and see if we can get a log

00:05:44.846 --> 00:05:46.446
- of visitors the past few weeks.
- Okay.

00:05:47.682 --> 00:05:51.085
So the thief entered here, but the
Rembrandt's all the way over there.

00:05:51.819 --> 00:05:54.264
Most thieves prefer not to bust
through the wall like the Kool-Aid Man.

00:05:54.288 --> 00:05:58.526
Okay, so this person took
the time to cut out the window,

00:05:58.659 --> 00:06:01.494
<i>toss down a rope, slide down right here.</i>

00:06:01.629 --> 00:06:04.966
And then just walks right by
Vermeer, Caravaggio,

00:06:05.099 --> 00:06:09.203
Turner, Rubens, Delacroix, and Goya?

00:06:09.337 --> 00:06:12.139
Do you have any idea how much
all of those are worth?

00:06:12.273 --> 00:06:13.593
I'm sure you're going to tell me.

00:06:13.674 --> 00:06:15.375
A lot more than the Rembrandt.

00:06:15.509 --> 00:06:16.978
If this heist was about money,

00:06:17.111 --> 00:06:19.471
the thief would have taken the
most valuable piece he could.

00:06:24.185 --> 00:06:26.587
<i>Our guy would have known that
this Goya was the real jackpot.</i>

00:06:26.721 --> 00:06:29.023
Maybe they didn't do their research.

00:06:29.156 --> 00:06:31.058
Every single detail
of this thing was planned.

00:06:31.192 --> 00:06:34.929
I mean, look at the frame, that perfectly
straight line down the inside seam.

00:06:35.062 --> 00:06:37.531
Removing this canvas
took precision and time.

00:06:37.665 --> 00:06:39.567
Somebody wanted this painting
for a reason.

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:42.203
Whoever the thief was, they
were not in it for the money.

00:06:42.336 --> 00:06:43.871
This was personal.

00:06:44.739 --> 00:06:45.873
They wanted her.

00:06:49.777 --> 00:06:51.444
Did you say 22 million?

00:06:51.579 --> 00:06:53.991
Yeah, but if Morgan's right, we need
to find out more about the Rembrandt

00:06:54.015 --> 00:06:57.385
to figure out who might have taken
it. And what their real motivation was.

00:07:08.095 --> 00:07:09.297
Excuse me.

00:07:09.429 --> 00:07:10.998
Is this Major Crimes?

00:07:11.132 --> 00:07:13.901
You must be Mr. Eastman. I'm
Captain Wagner, we spoke on the phone.

00:07:14.035 --> 00:07:15.836
Of course, please, call me Rhys.

00:07:15.970 --> 00:07:19.774
Rhys flew in from Mexico City this
morning to help us find our missing girl.

00:07:19.907 --> 00:07:23.644
Yeah, I had a lead on Kahlo's <i>La
Mesa Herida,</i> but it didn't pan out.

00:07:24.477 --> 00:07:26.113
Uh, help us how?

00:07:26.247 --> 00:07:29.951
I'm an art recovery specialist. I
recover lost, missing, or stolen art.

00:07:30.084 --> 00:07:32.461
They cram all the info right there
in the title, huh? That's helpful.

00:07:32.485 --> 00:07:34.956
- And you are?
- Gillory works with us as a consultant.

00:07:35.089 --> 00:07:38.458
She does, and she really feels as
though this painting has enough attention

00:07:38.592 --> 00:07:39.694
without flying someone in.

00:07:39.827 --> 00:07:41.429
Did the Fosters send you?

00:07:41.562 --> 00:07:44.799
No, the insurance company did. If I
can recover the Rembrandt safely,

00:07:44.932 --> 00:07:47.768
the insurance company can
avoid cutting a rather large check.

00:07:47.902 --> 00:07:50.571
Oh, good, good. What a relief.

00:07:50.705 --> 00:07:54.608
Okay, so this entire investigation is
about saving an insurance company money.

00:07:54.742 --> 00:07:58.346
That's awesome, right guys? Just wanted
to make sure you guys heard that. Go on.

00:07:58.478 --> 00:08:00.681
Morgan believes that the
Fosters' Rembrandt was targeted

00:08:00.815 --> 00:08:02.416
for a reason other than money.

00:08:04.118 --> 00:08:06.354
I mean, anything's possible,
but in my experience,

00:08:06.486 --> 00:08:08.689
- it's always about money.
- Mmm.

00:08:08.823 --> 00:08:10.624
Well, not this time.

00:08:10.758 --> 00:08:13.928
I mean, thieves don't steal masterpieces
to hang on their walls, Ms. Gillory.

00:08:14.662 --> 00:08:16.797
Maybe this one did, Mr. Eastman.

00:08:18.566 --> 00:08:19.800
Morgan and I'll go see

00:08:19.934 --> 00:08:21.478
what the Fosters can tell us
about their painting.

00:08:21.502 --> 00:08:23.237
Great. Fill in Rhys on the way.

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:27.808
Shall we?

00:08:39.854 --> 00:08:43.157
The moment we saw her at
auction, we knew we had to have her.

00:08:44.525 --> 00:08:46.961
I mean honestly,
we would have paid even more.

00:08:48.929 --> 00:08:50.331
We think she's priceless.

00:08:51.298 --> 00:08:53.968
Greg and I started a hedge fund
right out of college.

00:08:54.101 --> 00:08:56.804
We worked 80 hours a week
for decades.

00:08:56.937 --> 00:08:59.040
So by the time
we even thought about kids,

00:08:59.173 --> 00:09:03.044
we couldn't imagine chasing a
baby around here, making a mess.

00:09:03.177 --> 00:09:07.281
So, we often thought of the girl
in that painting as our daughter.

00:09:07.415 --> 00:09:09.626
Can you think of anyone who
may have wanted to steal from you?

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:11.318
No. You think this was personal?

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.556
- So, why share her?
- I'm sorry, what?

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:19.060
Mmm. Oh, just you're talking
about this painting like your daughter,

00:09:19.193 --> 00:09:21.062
and I've never put my daughter
in a museum.

00:09:21.195 --> 00:09:23.206
I'm just wondering why you
wouldn't keep it to yourself.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:27.068
Loaning out a masterpiece increases
its visibility and its reputation.

00:09:27.201 --> 00:09:29.870
And its value. Spend some time
in a museum, jacks up the price.

00:09:30.004 --> 00:09:31.314
You can sell it to the highest bidder.

00:09:31.338 --> 00:09:33.407
- She's not for sale.
- Mmm.

00:09:33.542 --> 00:09:35.352
Well, in my experience,
thieves are two things.

00:09:35.376 --> 00:09:37.278
They're greedy and chatty.

00:09:37.411 --> 00:09:39.180
And these masterpieces,

00:09:39.313 --> 00:09:42.059
they don't fetch the same price on the
black market as they do at an auction.

00:09:42.083 --> 00:09:44.051
So these thieves,
they like to talk to people.

00:09:44.185 --> 00:09:47.822
They ask around and all it will
take is one of these people to call me

00:09:47.955 --> 00:09:51.625
and I can help negotiate the
return of your lovely servant girl.

00:09:52.593 --> 00:09:54.328
Do you call her a servant girl?

00:09:55.096 --> 00:09:56.163
It's not a servant.

00:09:56.664 --> 00:09:57.698
Excuse me?

00:09:58.232 --> 00:10:00.768
She's leaning out the
windowsill looking for business.

00:10:00.901 --> 00:10:02.203
That's a working girl.

00:10:02.336 --> 00:10:04.872
Well, there's speculation that
the subject was a courtesan,

00:10:05.005 --> 00:10:07.245
but widely believed that
she was either a servant girl...

00:10:07.374 --> 00:10:09.610
A servant girl with a
gold braid? Come on.

00:10:09.743 --> 00:10:12.413
Look at the way she leans.
It's domestic, not provocative.

00:10:12.547 --> 00:10:16.417
It's upsetting, is what it is, because
she looks like a child, but she's working.

00:10:16.551 --> 00:10:18.018
She's contemplating life.

00:10:18.152 --> 00:10:20.921
- I-Is this important to the investigation?
- No, it's not.

00:10:21.055 --> 00:10:23.324
What else can you tell us
about the Rembrandt itself?

00:10:23.457 --> 00:10:27.428
The details about her
providence, they're all in here.

00:10:34.735 --> 00:10:37.606
This girl in the window's
traveled all over the world.

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:42.676
Paris, London, Berlin. She's lived
a much more exciting life than me.

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:45.222
Except now she's probably rolled
up in the back of somebody's van.

00:10:45.246 --> 00:10:49.116
Well, let's hope she got it all
out of her system first.

00:10:50.451 --> 00:10:52.319
- This is interesting.
- You got something?

00:10:52.453 --> 00:10:58.459
Maybe. Right after Rembrandt
painted the young girl in 1645, he sold it.

00:10:58.593 --> 00:11:01.153
At that point, it sort of bounced
around for a few hundred years,

00:11:01.262 --> 00:11:03.632
17th century Paris,
kind of skimmed this part,

00:11:03.764 --> 00:11:07.201
until it was purchased by a Prussian
nobleman who kept it until he died.

00:11:09.236 --> 00:11:11.138
Then his family kept it till 1932

00:11:11.272 --> 00:11:14.543
until Franz von Papen dissolved
the Free State of Prussia.

00:11:14.675 --> 00:11:16.253
I thought you said this was interesting.

00:11:16.277 --> 00:11:18.117
Look, I'm trying to care
about this case, okay?

00:11:18.212 --> 00:11:21.982
Which at the moment is just saving an
insurance company from having to pay money

00:11:22.116 --> 00:11:24.619
to a couple of people
who seem to be doing just fine.

00:11:24.752 --> 00:11:26.420
Where did she go next?

00:11:26.555 --> 00:11:30.991
To a Polish businessman in Kraków,
and he hung it in his family home.

00:11:31.125 --> 00:11:34.261
Then it just kind of bounced
around from collection to collection

00:11:34.395 --> 00:11:37.566
until good old Greg and Linda
paid a fortune for it.

00:11:37.698 --> 00:11:39.033
Why is any of this important?

00:11:39.668 --> 00:11:41.302
I don't know yet.

00:11:41.435 --> 00:11:43.813
Lab results came back on those
slags we found on the museum floor,

00:11:43.837 --> 00:11:47.007
tested positive for aluminum
oxide, so I did some research.

00:11:47.141 --> 00:11:49.376
<i>When aluminum
combines with ferric oxide,</i>

00:11:49.511 --> 00:11:52.079
<i>it creates a thermite reaction
hot enough to melt glass.</i>

00:11:52.213 --> 00:11:54.858
<i>Would explain why we didn't find
any glass shards under the sky light.</i>

00:11:54.882 --> 00:11:57.051
It also came up in a report
on another museum heist.

00:11:57.184 --> 00:12:00.454
Two years ago, a Matisse was stolen
from the Kunsthal Museum in Rotterdam.

00:12:00.589 --> 00:12:03.357
<i>And aluminum oxide was found
under the museum sky light.</i>

00:12:03.490 --> 00:12:05.627
Which might mean this
isn't our thief's first rodeo.

00:12:05.759 --> 00:12:07.261
You and Daphne look for others.

00:12:07.394 --> 00:12:10.898
So far we found 19 heists around
the world with the same MO.

00:12:11.031 --> 00:12:14.636
Always a masterpiece stolen from a
gallery. Always worth 10 to 30 million.

00:12:14.768 --> 00:12:16.904
And traces of aluminum oxide
at every scene

00:12:17.037 --> 00:12:19.541
under a window
or a skylight just like ours.

00:12:19.674 --> 00:12:21.275
We have any idea who it might be?

00:12:21.408 --> 00:12:24.345
Well, the internet seems to think
so. Some call him Jean-Baptiste.

00:12:24.478 --> 00:12:27.781
- He's French?
- No, but the first painting he stole was.

00:12:27.915 --> 00:12:30.084
"<i>The White Duck</i>
by Jean-Baptiste Oudrey."

00:12:30.217 --> 00:12:31.785
Stolen in Paris, 12 years ago.

00:12:32.353 --> 00:12:34.121
Tell me somebody's got eyes on him.

